have the highest opinion possible of the Knabe Plano,\nwhich possesses qualities of action and varieties of tone-color that\nmake it wonderfully responsive to artistic demands.\u201d\nTSCHAIKOVSKY:\u2014\u201cCombines with great volume of tone rare, sympa\nthetic and noble tone-color and perfect action.\"\nCARRENO:\u2014\u201cMy expectations... .as to the Knabe Pianos were even sur\npassed by the reality.\"\nHAMBOURGt\u2014\"A pianist having such a wonderful instrument under his\nAngers Is able to express his innermost thoughts.\"\nVON BtlliOWi\u2014\u201cTheir sound and touch are more sympathetic to my ears\nand hands than all others of the country.\"\nD'ALBERT:\u2014\u201cFrom fullest.conviction, X declare them to be the best instru\nments in America.\u201d\nJESSE FRENCH\nPIANO ft ORGAN CO.\nBirmingham, Ala., 2018 Second Avenue, i\nJ. H. HOLCOMBE, Manager.\nAMERICA SIXTY YEARS AGO.\nInteresting Facts Concerning Life and\nHabits in the United States.\n\u2022\u25a0Penn,\" in the Philadelphia Bulletin.\nThe Meriden Britannia company, in\nConnecticut, has for some time past been\npublishing a half dozen numbers, each\nyear, of a little periodical called The\nSilver Standard, in connection with its\nsystem of advertising its wares. In each\nnumber there is a collation of curious and\noften highly interesting facts concern\ning life, habits and various conditions\nin the United States in tile early days.\nWe had occasion once before to refer to\nthese citations in Illustrating a compari\nwon between 1840 and 1908, and the copy\nnow at hand is somewhat similarly sug\ngestive as to 1847 and 1007. in the light\nof Its reproductions of contemporaneous\nstatements it gives at least a glimpse,\nhere and there, of agitations, enterprises\nand current thought In the former period,\nand it is interesting to note how some of\nthem were parallel to kindred ones which\nnow occupy the public mind.\nFor example, toward the close of 1847\nthere was a money stringency, together\nwith such hoardings of casli as nearly\nbroke the Bank of England. American\nfinances, too, under the Polk administra\ntion, were charged with having been con\nducted In violation of pledges as to the\nlimitation of expenditures and loans. At\nthat lime, however, the treasury had no\nsurplus; the debt contracted in tile Mexi\ncan war bad swallowed up available re\nsoftrees, and more money was required to\nmeet tlie balances that were against the\n(pivermnent. But wheat and corn were\nabundant; the com crop was estimated\nat 80e.it00.00t) bushels, and In an article on\nthe thrift and enterprise of the popula\ntion of New England, a writer, presum\nably a whig, put the question: \"Can\nPolk's free trade crush such a people?\"\nThanksgiving Day had Just been cele\nbrated In New- England, and life in that\npart of the country In 1847 Is particularly\nreflected in the excerpts. Boston, with a\npopulation of 314,000, was pointed to 'by\nthe New York Journal of Commerce as\nan example of astonishing growth. In\nthe accumulation of fortunes It seems\nthat \u201chundred thousand dollar men were\nplenty about,\u201d and that even \u201cmillionaires\nwere found here and there.\u201d\nAmerican clocks had reached such per\nfection, it was stated, that time pieces\nmade In Connecticut and warranted to\n\u201ckeep good reckoning\u201d were sold for Go\ncents at wholesale and $3 for retail, and\nat one manufactory 800 of them were\nproduced in a single day. There is also an\naccount of the Yankee peddlers of the\ntime and their carts tilled with \u201cthim\nbles, histories of the United States, maple\nsugar, flne-tooth combs, soap, life of\nGeneral Jackson, jackknives, bracelets,\ntoothpick, earrings, moral philosophy,\nglass cement;\u201d Yankee Silsbee, as a de\nlineator on the stage of that type of char\nacter, is pictured in his quaint rural garb;\nand It was said that many flourishing\ncharacters have commenced life in. the\nsume humble avocation.\nOne of the national ambitions of the\ntime was to see a fleet of steamships fly\ning the Stars and Stripes, on the Atlantic,\nand arrangements, it appears, had been\ncompleted between the government and\nE. K. Collins for the line of American\"\nsteamships between New York and Liver\npool\u2014the afterward noted but 111-fated\nCollins Line. Two locomotives which the\n\u2022Charleston Courier described as \u201csplendid\npieces of mechanism,\u201d had been made by\nRoss Winans of Baltimore for use in\nSouth Carolina\u2014one the \u201cJohn C. Cal\nhoun\u201d and the other the \u201cRough and\nReady\u201d (General Taylor.) \u201cThe former,\u201d\nit was said, \u201cbrings to mind the illustri\nous statesmen, in the purple and splendor\nof the Senate; the later, the indomitable\nhero in his farmer dress, plain, yet Invin\ncible on the field of battle.\u201d\nAds illustrated with good cuts are\ntrade winners\u2014The Gawk makes good\ncuts.\nMisuse of Banking Resources\nIn Gambling Brings Revolt\nOUTLOOK STILL* GLOOMY\nGreat Confusion Exists As to Pros\npects for Better Industrial and\nBusiness Activity\u2014Mercantile\nDepression Is Expected.\nBY W. G. NICHOLAS.\nNew York, December 14.\u2014(Special.)\n\u2014The inopportune bulge in the slyock\nmarket checked Investment buying and\nhas engendered a feeling of distrust\nas to the genuineness of bull senti\nment in Wall street. The misuse of\nbanking resources for speculation In\nBtocks was followed by a general and\nemphatic revolt on the part of the bus\niness community and there came a re\nflection of the same protest from\nWashington. It was made known to\nthe banking Interests that the treas\nury looked with disfavor upon Wall\nstreet activity at this time, following\nso close on the heels of extraordinary\nI governmental efforts for relief from\n11min( iu i uuuBinuuun.\nA still, small voice of warning was\nlieard and Wall street was admonished\nthat it was in extremely bad taste to\nuse the money and credit advanced\nby the government to stlmplate, and\nencourage stock gambling. The hint\nwas broadly given that it would be\nthe part of wisdom for the New York\nbanka to retire their $100,0o0,000 or so\nclearing house certificates before turn\ning their real money Into the stock\ngamble. Bluntly stated, the admoni\ntion was to sober up and not to pro\nlong the drunk with money obtained\nunder stress as a sort of compulsory\nloan on the credit of the government.\nNot that many stocks are not dirt\ncheap at current quotations, but con\nservative sentiment Is at this time\nstrongly opposed to Artificial efforts to\nmark up prices for apparently the only\npurpose of enabling overloaded banks\nand trust companies to shove out se\ncurities held by them as collateral on\nloans, and for window dressing that\ninsurance companies and other Insti\ntutions might make favorable end of\nthe year reports of condition. The\nprogramme mapped out weeks ago was\nto give the market such support as\nmight be necessary to prevent panicky\nslumps, but to discourugtc speculative\nexpansion. The unwjse hull movement\naround the first of the month was a\ndeparture from this plan and the re\nsult has been unfortunate.\nIt has filled the public mind with\nopen distrust and has seemingly post\nponed the time for a healthy begin\nning of permanent improvement. A\ngenuine bull campaign cannot he en\ngineered on clearing house certificates\ndescribed previously In this column as\nan Issue of currency based on the\nequities in unredeemed pawn tickets\n(unpaid collateral in the hands of\nhanks). By others it is disrespectfully\ncalled \u201cRoosevelt currency.** At any\nr THE THAniyQ and REPRESENTATIVE BUSINESS COLLEGE OF i'HE SOUTH\nSuccess Awaits You\nin the BusinessWorld.\nThe young man or woman with a thorough understanding of the prac\ntices of the modem business office can command the very best salaries\u2014\ntheir services are sought. We have daily inquiries for bookkeepers and\nI stenographers\u2014'the energetic and ambitious kind.\nA Complete Course in Bookkeeping\nOr Stenography for $35 if You\nEnroll Before the 20th of December\nIn telling you of this reduced rate we want to especially remind you that\nthe course*of study is just the same as if you paid the regular rate, and\nthe same teachers instruct you. That means Perfection.\nCall in and let\u2019s talk it over. If this is not convenient just drop us a\npostal or telephone to us and we will tell you about it fully.\nWheeler Business\nWillard J. Wheeler /p /YO Potter Building,\nPresident f f W W Birmingham4\nrate business men are fully minded to\ncontinue energetic protests against the\nuse of money for stock speculation on\nwhich they should have the first call.\nMoney continues to be the controlling\nfactor in the Wall street section.\nFunds are slow In accumulating, the'\nreturn flow rates for call money are\nkept abnormally high in the hope of\nattracting funds from the outside, but\nthis is one of the times when the mag\nnet does not seem to work right.\nThe higher the banks mark up In\nterest the more distrustful the outside\nseems to get, the action being con\nstrued seemingly as an Indication that\nthe New York bankeVs fear more\ntrouble and are trying to fortify* them\nselves against It with outside help.\nThis being the view taken, Interior\nmoney. Instead of being forwarded to\nthis center, Is held tighter than ever\nby the owners\u2014a most embarrassing\nsituation for the big- money city.\nOf course tills sort of thing will not\nlast forever, and there will ere long\nbo a return to the normal. Meantime\nhanks everywhere are straightening\ntheir reserves and putting off as long\nas possible the day for an unrestricted\nreturn to cash payments. The fear\namong them Is widespread that the\nopening of the doors to a resumption\nof business along normal lines will be\na signal for wholesale withdrawal of\nfunds.\nThey are keeping their bands on the\npulBe of public feeling and at the right\ntime there will he a simultaneous re\nsumption In the largo communities. It\nmay be that this hoped for day will not\narrive until after the turn of the new\nyear, now only two weelcs distant.\nOne of the strong grounds for the\nadvocacy of a central bank under gov\nernment auspices, modeled after that\nof Great Britain or Germany, Is that\nit will safeguard the country from the\npossible danger of money niurket ma\nnipulation by any conspiracy ol\u2019 very\nrich men who might be able to obtain\ncontrol of formidable sums of rush.\nlivents of recent occurrence are an\nobject lesHon of what might lie done\nIn this regard. Very late history has\nshown that there was enough money In\nthe hands of a small coterie of wealthy\nmen to have created a panic Infinitely\nmore murderous than anything yet\nseen. There are half a dozen men now\non the stage of affairs who could In\ncombination lock up and withdraw\nfrom circulation at any time they might\nso desire $200,000,0(10 to $260,000,000\nof their own, thus precipitating busi\nness disaster without warning.\nAs a matter of fact a group of men\nno larger In number than mentioned\naid actually convert shocks into cash\nto an aggregate amount of fully a quar\nter of a billion dollars, which was\navailable for their use 60 days ago. If\nthey had been real sure enough con\nspirators of the kihd seen In Wash\nington visions it would have been en\ntirely within their power to have\nbrought ruin upon the country. Not\nbeing conspirators they banded togeth\ner for the relief of a distressed situa\ntion, using their money for the most\nlaudable of purposes and not to dis\ncredit any administration or bring any\nbody\u2019s policies into disrepute.\nIt nevertheless remains clear that\nmalevolent combinations for sinister\npurposes might very easily be formed\nwith money enough to wreck business\nor engineer wild speculation at pleas\nure as matters now stand. A great cen\ntral bank, with proper powers, would\nmake such a combination impossible.\nWhen the fug clears and people are\nable to get a better view of what has\nhappened and to connect events in\nproper sequence, it may even be\ncharged that the man who came to the\nrescue when panicky conditions ruled\nreally brought about the stringency by\nselling out their securities for cash ami\nI keeping it where they could get hold\nof it at will. The defense will, of\ncourse, be raised, that they did this be\ncause they saw the storm coming anil\nprepared themselves to meet it, thereby\nobserving the dictates of prudence, in\nstead of being improperly iniluenced\nby a desire to create disaster.\nGreat confusion exists as to the in\ndustrial and business outlook. There\nIs seemingly a large amount of sub\nstantial testimony that many Import\nant industries are tugging at the leash\nready to resume full activity as soon\nas permitted. On the other side there\nis a well defined skepticism. Special- I\nIsts In the various Industries are saying\namong themselves, \u201cYes, there Is ap\nparently a lot of business in sight, but\nhow can we do the business unless\nwe have money to swing it, and how\ncan people pay for our goods unless\nthey can command the money, and how\nls there going to he money unless af\nfairs resume a natural position?\u201d\nThere seems to have been formed a\ncircle and everybody is traveling\naround, around and around in their\nspeculation as to what is going to hap\npen. Doubtless the fundamentals are\ncontinually hardening and conditions\nbecoming more healthy, yet visible evi\ndences thereof are not overwhelmingly\nconclusive at the moment.\nNine out of ten men you see ex\npect mercantile depression after the\nfirst of the year, and further slowing\ndown and economizing wherever pos\nsible. A dropping off in railroad earn\nings Is one of the tilings looked for,\naccompanied by a letting off of men.\nDividends, unless earned, will not be\npaid because of the difficulty In get\nting money.\nThere will doubtless also be a sud\nden disappearance or reduction In many\nof those fascinating paper surpluses\nwhich have been adorning the annual\nreports of corporations\u2014surpluses\nwhloh represent triumphs of bookkeep\ning, but which have little more than i\njunk heap value.\nThe action of the Western Union Tel\negraph company In substituting Its\n\u25a0tock dividend of iy\u00ab per cent for the\nusual cash dividend may be the begin\nning of a similar movement on the j\npart of other corporations. At the pres- i\nent market price of Wrestern Union the\nstock dividend is equivalent to a casli i\npayment of about %ths. The action\nlias aroused considerable criticism and\nhas provoked the sneers of the un-\nrighteous. Every increase In the vol\nume of a stock which is not earning\nits dividends thins the substance ami\nmakes the capitalization of less value.\nBy and by, If the thing is kept, up, it\nwill be a. case of subtracting from a\nminus quantity.\nThe copper specialists are talking\nmost dolefully. They are viewing the\nfuture through the bluest of glasses.\nThey are rather overdoing it, perhaps,\nbut they are no longer open to the\ncharge of wilfully deceiving themselves\non the hopeful side.\nThe mines are doing the best thing\nthat qould be done In reducing pro\nduction. With a fair resumption of\nIndustrial activity after the first of the\nyear stocks in sight should be re\nduced to a manageable amount by the\nend of six months.\nSenator Clark of Montana, the richest\nindividual copper miner in the world,\nexpresses the opinion that by the end\nof 1908 stocks should be reduced to\nabout the right dimensions and that\nthe metal will be on a price basis of\nabout 16 *centa, which he declares to bo\nhigh enough.\nThe Jews and the Christmas Spirit.\nFrom I^eslle's Weekly.\nSo many Jews now observe Christmas\nDay to the extent of exchanging gifts\nthat the remarks of Rabbi Emil G. Tllrsch\nof Chicago on what the Jew celebrates\nat the Christmas season have a peculiar\nInterest. He points out the fact that\nHanukah, the Jewish feast of lights, oc\ncuring on the 26th day of the midwinter\nmonth of the Jewish calendar, has a\ncharacter of rejoicing that makes it akin\nto the Christian holiday. It commemor\nates the victory of the Maccabees over\nthe Syrians and the rededication of the\nTemple, but its observance has come to\ntake the form, In the main, of a \u2022chil\ndren\u2019s festival, as Christmas does, and\nI)r. Hlrsch says the custom of decorating\nChristmas trees with candles was borrow\ned from the Jewish usage In the celebra\ntion of Hanukah.\nWhile assorting that \u201cthe Christmas\nsentiment of \u2018good-will to me' is cer\ntainly nn echo of the convictions and\naspirations which the Jewish festival of\nlights emphasizes,\u2019* and believing that\nThe actuaTvital facts of the beverage ques\ntion are these:\u2014The most healthful drink in\nworld is (linger Ale, if it is an article with real\nbodv to it, with flavor, with substance and\npurity, such as ALE o\u00a3 GINGER has proven\nitself to be. This b tan cl has earned a remark\nable sale and popularity upon its inherent\nmerit. Try it today and you will endorse it.\n4c a Glass at all F<funta\nlie a Bottle fl.tS a Dozen\ndostkh-northiivoton nitna co.\nDlSTRlRUTiCRS.\nJg-.-Tt i\nsooner or later tlie two festivals will ho\ncelebrated on the same day, Dr. Hirsch\ncalls attention to the shameful fact that\neven now, in some parts of Europe\u2014par\nticularly In Russia\u2014Christmas is a day\non which fanatical mobs are prone to at\ntack their Jewish neighbors. \"The Jew\ncannot rejoice,\" he says, \"nor sing of\ngood-will, when he knows that the day\nof his joy has been and is the day of\nhis helpless brothers\u2019 trembling and anxi\nety and agony. *th this country, the Jew\nrejoices that the Christinas sentiment In\nspeedily and beautifully progressing to\nward realization in action. And when he\nsees the lights leap into glory in his\nneighbors\u2019 homes be breathes for tha fer\nvent prayer for their happiness. He glad\nly contributes his part to the happiness\nof his friends, and such as share with him\nthe hospitality of his domestic hearth, but\nare not of Ills religion fraternity. Fol\nhimself ami hie own, however, an yet he\nprefers to welt.\"\nDoubtless the Reason.\nFrom Harper\u2019s Weekly.\nProf. Rearchem was engrossed in the\nstudy of all things that crawled. To him\na pin lhad but one purpose\u2014to Impale in\nseota; tin cans lmt one use\u2014to house\nworms.\n\u25a0\u2019Professor,\" complained his young wife\nono evening, how the prices of vegeta\nbles are soaring! Just think of It, t- for\nthis bushel of apples, and half have\nworms In them.\"\n\"Perhaps, darling.\u201d commented the pro\nfessor. as he strove to part the few re\nmaining hairs on his Hhlnlog head, \"they\nare of a very rare species.\u201d\nGIVEN AWAY FREE\ni\nKENNY S BEAUTIFUL\nCHRISTMAS SOUVENIR\nCONSISTING OF\nA HANDSOME PLATE\nBeautifully Painted, Entitled\n\u201cThe Happy Little Boy and His Dog\u201d\nFREE! Given Away FREE!\nSaturday December 21\nC. D. KENNY CO.\nTeas, Coffees, Sugars\n319 North 20th Street, Birmingham. 1928 Second Avenue, Bessemer.\nYou know what Kenny\u2019s Christmas Souvenirs always are. This year they are\nfiner than ever, so do not fail to get one next Saturday,","height":"27820","width":"19904"}}
